# NOTE: Keep this list short (~8 entries). Remove old ones as new ones land.
CHANGELOG = [
    "b460: mining items now wear hand-picked RESERVE sprites with transparent backgrounds. Pulled the sprite-assets-v1 reserve, built a keyed picker (sprite_package/picks_mining: candidates shown chroma-keyed on a checkerboard so the real in-game look is what you pick), chose all 14, and ran apply_mining_sprites.py -- which keys each reserve PNG's dark background to transparent (border-median key + edge despill) and promotes the webp into canonical_pool_full.pkl (status=reserve). The 10 ores + 4 Ioun Stones each map to a distinct keyed gem/mineral/dust sprite (e.g. Adamantine Dust = a rainbow sparkle-dust pile, Ruby = a red cluster, the Iouns = faceted gems/crystals). All 14 verified to render non-empty through render_item_icon with proper alpha. Picker tooling (build_mining_picker.py with a per-item Suggested strip, build_mining_picker_curated.py, apply_mining_sprites.py) committed for future swaps.",
    "b459: every mining item now has its own icon. The 10 ore ingredients and 4 Ioun Stones were sharing a handful of gem pids; each now maps to a DISTINCT in-pool sprite, hand-picked by rendering montages of all the gem/mineral/metal sprites in the canonical pool and eyeballing colour + shape. Ores: Iron Chunk->Iron Bark chunk, Copper Nugget->copper pouch, Stone Shard->Stone Flower crystal, Silver Vein->Quicksilver bead, Gold Flake->gold wisp, Coal Ember->dark cluster, Mithril Shard->blue gem, Ruby Fragment->red gem, Diamond Chip->cut gem, Adamantine Dust->sparkling dust. Ioun Stones: Fortitude/Might/Agility use the blue/green/white Orb-of-Vitality crystals, Mastery uses the ornate gold+diamond brooch to read as the premium capstone. No two share a pid; all 14 verified to resolve + render through render_item_icon. Still reuse (not bespoke) art -- a few overlap a known item's icon -- but it's a clear step up from the all-same-gem placeholder; bespoke PNGs tracked in MINING_TODO.md.",
    "b458: removed the artificial 3-mines-per-floor cap and checked the ore economy. A vein is a finite 5-10 tile worm and mining one tile opens the next for tunnelling, so the vein's own length is the natural per-floor limit -- no arbitrary cap needed. Dropped MINE_LIMIT_PER_FLOOR and every gate on it (game_systems, app.py 'm' handler, harness); gs.dwarf_mines_per_floor survives only as a stat counter. Economy then measured two ways: a drop-table model over deep ~17-vein runs (~13 of each common ore, 5-8 uncommon, 0.7-2.6 rare; ~547 gem-gold) and 20 live no-fog dwarf playtests. The cap was the blocker -- live mining went from ~2 to ~10 attempts/run and Ioun-Stone crafts from 0 to 14 across 20 runs (7 worn). Curve validated: the three cheap stones (Fortitude/Might/Agility) are readily craftable on a deep run while Mastery (Ruby x2 + Diamond + Adamantine) lands in only ~21% -- a real capstone grind. Drop rates and recipe costs left as-is; they're well-tuned now. Remaining limiter is dwarf survival (the policy pilots the melee dwarf into early deaths), which is a separate combat-AI issue tracked in MINING_TODO.md, not an economy gap.",
    "b457: the playtester now runs the WHOLE mining loop, not just opportunistic swings. New proactive vein-seeking (_mining_target_obs BFS-paths to the nearest reachable floor tile next to a known ore vein; the smart policy detours there, bounded by the per-floor cap and skipped while wedged). New crafting: a dwarf with enough mined ore opens the craft menu and makes the highest-tier Ioun Stone it can afford (_pick_craftable_ioun + game_loop/inventory triggers). New equipping: the policy wears a crafted Ioun Stone (e<N> -> equip_accessory), prioritised above food-crafting so it isn't starved -- verified end-to-end (opens inventory, equips within ~2 steps, stats apply). Also fixed a pre-existing dwarf trap: non-casters (max_mana 0) with a spell slot looped i->m->x trying to memorize spells they can never cast, burning ~half a dwarf run; the memorize intent is now gated on can_cast (casters unaffected). On surviving runs the dwarf mines plenty (e.g. 15 mines to F12); live Ioun crafting stays rare because the ore economy is tight (cheapest stone = 4 specific commons vs ~1 ore/run) -- a balance lever tracked in MINING_TODO.md, not a code gap.",
    "b456: the headless playtester now mines. Extracted the mining core into game_systems.py (MINE_LIMIT_PER_FLOOR, dwarf_adjacent_vein_directions, dwarf_mining_available, process_mine_action) so the app key-handler and the playtest harness share ONE implementation instead of a copy. The harness gained an obs['mining'] field, an 'm' game_loop action + mine_direction_mode dispatch, and a smart-policy intent: a dwarf adjacent to an ore vein (with floor budget left and no monster next door) swings the pick, then picks the vein direction. Verified the 3-per-floor cap holds via direct test (locked out at 3 even with fresh adjacent veins, and per-floor independent); dwarves mine opportunistically across seeds (0-7 mines/run), humans never do, no new crashes. Mining is currently opportunistic-only (the agent mines veins it walks next to) -- proactive vein-seeking + report counters are tracked in MINING_TODO.md along with the sprite/limit/recipe finishing work.",
    "b455: dwarf mining is in. Ore veins now snake through the walls of most floors (a 5-10 tile worm of minable '#'). Dwarves -- and only dwarves -- sense them: step next to one and you get 'You sense mineral deposits in the wall to the north!', the tile shows as an amber '%' on the map, and a 'm = mine' hint appears. Mining (m, then a direction) smashes the vein into open floor, capped at 3 per floor, with a 75% drop: usually an ore crafting ingredient (Iron Chunk up to Adamantine Dust, weighted by rarity), sometimes a sellable gem worth straight gold that scales with depth. The ore feeds a new dwarf-only recipe family: four Ioun Stones (Fortitude/Might/Agility/Mastery) -- orbiting gem accessories that grant real, registered stat bonuses (+HP/Def, +Str/Atk, +Dex, or the all-round Mastery) while equipped. Veins, detection state, and per-floor mine counts all persist through saves. NON-mining fix riding along: crafting now counts stacked ingredients by their .count instead of by object, so any recipe needing 2+ of a stacking ingredient (i.e. nearly every potion) is actually craftable, and crafting consumes the exact amount instead of wiping a whole stack.",
    "b454: three combat-screen polish fixes from on-device testing. (1) Victory music no longer starts before the final blow lands -- the fanfare was scheduled at 1800ms but the monster doesn't grey out until 2100ms and the DEFEATED overlay doesn't flash until 2700ms, so the sting spoiled the kill. Victory music now fires at DEFEAT_OVERLAY_MS (2700ms), landing with the overlay. (2) Killed the stray scrollbar on the combat/map screen: #content-area kept overflow-y:auto and the 200px room-panel + map + chips overflowed by a hair, exposing the styled 8px track. Hidden the bar on #content-area only (scrollbar-width:none + ::-webkit-scrollbar display:none) -- touch-scroll still works for tall views, and inner inventory/vendor lists keep their own bars. (3) Combat-card text is now flush-left: the monster and player panels inherited text-align:center from .bottom-pinned-zone, so each line (name / Lv / HP+MP bars / A:D:) centred raggedly in its column. Added #monster_panel,#player_panel{text-align:left} so the stats line up cleanly beside the sprite.",
    "b453: two combat-feel fixes. (1) Fleeing no longer takes three taps -- FLEE was registered as a 'dangerous command' so it armed a two-tap 'tap again to confirm' before even rolling, on top of the direction d-pad that follows a successful escape. But flee is a defensive escape, not an irreversible act like deleting a save or sacrificing at an altar, and picking a flee direction (with FIGHT to cancel) is already a natural confirm. Dropped 'f' from the dangerous-command list, so it's now FLEE -> roll -> pick a direction. (2) The monster-defeat animation timeline is now tunable from one spot: the hardcoded 2100ms grayscale, 2700ms DEFEATED-overlay, and 4500ms panel-auto-dismiss are now DEFEAT_GRAYSCALE_MS / DEFEAT_OVERLAY_MS / DEFEAT_DISMISS_MS in game_state.py, read by generate_monster_defeat_js and the dismiss timer. The log/toast reveal (DEFEAT_LOG_REVEAL_MS) now derives from DEFEAT_OVERLAY_MS + 600 so it always lands just after the overlay flashes, even if the timeline is retuned.",
]

